{"title_page": "Hespererato rubra", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| taxon =Hespererato rubra\n| image = \n| image_caption =  \n| authority = Fehse, 2016\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"WoRMS\" />\n| synonyms =\n| display_parents = 3\n}}\n\n'''''Hespererato rubra''''' is a [[species]] of small [[sea snail]], a [[marine (ocean)|marine]] [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Eratoidae]], the false cowries or trivias and allies<ref name=\"WoRMS\">MolluscaBase (2018). Hespererato rubra Fehse, 2016. Accessed through: World Register of Marine Species at: http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=877616 on 2018-07-18</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThis marine species occurs off [[Cebu Island]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Fehse D. (2016). Contributions to the knowledge of the Eratoidae. XI. New species in the genus Hespererato F.A. Schilder, 1925. Neptunea. 14(1): 30\u201336. page(s): 33, pl. 2 figs 1\u20133\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q56274268}}\n\n[[Category:Eratoidae]]\n[[Category:Gastropods described in 2016]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| taxon =Hespererato rubra\n| image = \n| image_caption =  \n| authority = Fehse, 2016\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"WoRMS\" />\n| synonyms =\n| display_parents = 3\n}}\n\n'''''Hespererato rubra''''' is a [[species]] of small [[sea snail]], a [[marine (ocean)|marine]] [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Eratoidae]], the false cowries or trivias and allies<ref name=\"WoRMS\">MolluscaBase (2018). Hespererato rubra Fehse, 2016. Accessed through: World Register of Marine Species at: http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=877616 on 2018-07-18</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThis marine species occurs off [[Cebu Island]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Fehse D. (2016). Contributions to the knowledge of the Eratoidae. XI. New species in the genus Hespererato F.A. Schilder, 1925. Neptunea. 14(1): 30\u201336. page(s): 33, pl. 2 figs 1-3\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q56274268}}\n\n[[Category:Eratoidae]]\n[[Category:Gastropods described in 2016]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hespererato_rubra"}
{"title_page": "Opioid rotation", "text_new": "'''Opioid rotation'''&nbsp;or&nbsp;'''opioid switching'''&nbsp;is the process of changing one opioid to another to improve [[pain]] control or reduce unwanted [[side effect]]s.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite journal |last1=Kraychete |first1=DC |last2=Sakata |first2=RK |title=Use and rotation of opioids in chronic non-oncologic pain. |journal=Revista Brasileira de Anestesiologia |date=July 2012 |volume=62 |issue=4 |pages=554\u201362 |doi=10.1016/S0034-7094(12)70155-1 |pmid=22793972}} {{open access}}</ref> This technique was introduced in the 1990s to help manage severe chronic pain and improve the opioid response in [[cancer]] patients.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal |last1=Mercadante |first1=S |last2=Bruera |first2=E |title=Opioid switching in cancer pain: From the beginning to nowadays. |journal=Critical Reviews in Oncology/Hematology |date=March 2016 |volume=99 |pages=241\u20138 |doi=10.1016/j.critrevonc.2015.12.011 |pmid=26806145}} {{open access}}</ref> In order to obtain adequate levels of pain relief, patients requiring chronic opioid therapy may require an increase in the original prescribed dose for a number of reasons, including increased pain or a worsening disease state.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Peppin|first=John|date=2014-10-17|title=Toward a systematic approach to opioid rotation|journal=Journal of Pain Research|language=English|volume=7|pages=589\u2013608|doi=10.2147/jpr.s55782|pmid=25378948|pmc=4207581}}</ref> Over the course of long term treatment, an increase in dosage cannot be continued indefinitely as unwanted side effects&nbsp;of treatment often become intolerable once a certain dose is reached, even though the pain may still not be properly managed. One solution to this is to switch the patient between different opioid drugs over time, usually every few months.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Nalamachu|first=Srinivas R.|date=2012-10-01|title=Opioid Rotation in Clinical Practice|journal=Advances in Therapy|language=en|volume=29|issue=10|pages=849\u2013863|doi=10.1007/s12325-012-0051-7|pmid=23054690|issn=0741-238X}}</ref> Opioid rotation requires strict monitoring in patients with ongoing levels of high opioid doses for extended periods of time, since long term opioid use can lead to a patient developing&nbsp;[[Drug tolerance|tolerance]]&nbsp;to the analgesic effects of the drug.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Knotkova|first=Helena|last2=Fine|first2=Perry G.|last3=Portenoy|first3=Russell K.|title=Opioid Rotation: The Science and the Limitations of the Equianalgesic Dose Table|journal=Journal of Pain and Symptom Management|volume=38|issue=3|pages=426\u2013439|doi=10.1016/j.jpainsymman.2009.06.001|pmid=19735903|year=2009}}</ref> Patients may also not respond to the first opioid prescribed to them at all, therefore needing to try another opioid to help manage their pain.<ref name=\":1\" /> A patient's specific response and sensitivity to opioids include many factors that include physiology, genetics and pharmacodynamic parameters, which together determine the amount of pain control and tolerance of a particular opioid.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Mechanism ==\nOpioid analgesic drugs tend to exhibit incomplete [[cross-tolerance]], so that even when a patient has developed a high level of tolerance to one drug from this class, they may find that a different opioid drug will still be effective.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Gordon | first1 = D | last2 = Inturrisi | first2 = CE | last3 = Greensmith | first3 = JE | last4 = Brennan | first4 = TJ | last5 = Goble | first5 = L | last6 = Kerns | first6 = RD | date = May 2008 | title = Perioperative pain management in the opioid-tolerant individual | url = | journal = J Pain | volume = 9 | issue = 5| pages = 383\u20137 | doi = 10.1016/j.jpain.2008.01.331 | pmid = 18337186 }}</ref> The reasons for this are still not completely understood, but are thought to result from variations in [[opioid receptor]] [[Dissociation constant#Protein-ligand binding|affinity]] and occupancy levels at [[equianalgesic]] doses, as well as additional mechanisms of action possessed by some drugs such as the [[NMDA antagonist]] action of [[methadone]] or [[levorphanol]], or the [[SNRI]] activity of [[tramadol]] or [[tapentadol]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Smith | first1 = HS | last2 = Peppin | first2 = JF | date = Oct 2014 | title = Toward a systematic approach to opioid rotation | journal = J Pain Res | volume = 7 | issue = | pages = 589\u2013608 | doi = 10.2147/JPR.S55782 | pmid = 25378948 | pmc = 4207581 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Passik | first1 = SD | last2 = Webster | first2 = L | year = 2014 | title = Opioid analgesics: does potency matter? | url = | journal = J Opioid Manag | volume = 10 | issue = 4| pages = 263\u201375 | doi = 10.5055/jom.2014.0214 | pmid = 25162606 }}</ref>\n\n== Indications ==\nThere are no clinical guidelines outlining the use and implementation of opioid rotation.  However, this strategy is commonly used for these various situations: pain not controlled by current opioid, pain controlled but in the presence of intolerable adverse events, pain not controlled despite rapid increase in opioid dose, switching to utilize different alternative routes of administration, or switching due to high cost of current opioid (or other patient-specific cost considerations).<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mercadante|first=Sebastiano|last2=Bruera|first2=Eduardo|title=Opioid switching: A systematic and critical review|journal=Cancer Treatment Reviews|volume=32|issue=4|pages=304\u2013315|doi=10.1016/j.ctrv.2006.03.001|pmid=16624490|year=2006}}</ref>\n\n==Potential issues==\nWhile there is good evidence for the efficacy of opioid rotation as a treatment approach in general, there is less evidence for what particular opioid analgesics are most suitable, and in practice the choice of opioid drugs used depends on many factors such as patient characteristics, prescriber preferences and safety. One issue with opioid rotation is that an opioid therapy failure poorly predicts whether other opioids would be effective. In certain situations, multiple switches may be required before pain therapy is optimized.<ref>Fine, Perry G, and Russell K Portenoy. \u201cStrategies for Opioid Rotation: Decision Support in Chronic Pain Management.\u201d Medscape, Medscape, 30 Mar. 2010, www.medscape.org/viewarticle/717832.</ref> In addition, recent studies explore which opioid drugs are most effective in implementing in an opioid rotation, but have so far found no difference in efficacy between opioid drugs like methadone and fentanyl in cancer patients.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1089/jpm.2017.0301 | volume=20 | title=Response to the Article \"Overall Survival among Cancer Patients Undergoing Opioid Rotation to Methadone Compared to Other Opioids\" | year=2017 | journal=Journal of Palliative Medicine | pages=1184\u20131185 | last1 = van den Beuken-van Everdingen | first1 = Marieke H.J. | last2 = van Kuijk | first2 = Sander M.J. | last3 = Joosten | first3 = Elbert A.}}</ref>\n\nDiversion of prescribed opioid drugs for illicit recreational use is also a particular concern in this field, as the drugs which are most effective for relieving [[suffering]] in [[palliative care]] also tend to be those most sought after by [[Substance abuse|drug abusers]]. The choice of what opioid drug to use in which patient thus tends to be a balance between many different factors that must be considered, and the need for opioid rotation in chronic pain patients makes it advantageous for a wide range of different opioid drugs to be available, even though they may be broadly equivalent in action when used in shorter term treatment.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Cheung | first1 = CW | last2 = Qiu | first2 = Q | last3 = Choi | first3 = SW | last4 = Moore | first4 = B | last5 = Goucke | first5 = R | last6 = Irwin | first6 = M | year = 2014 | title = Chronic opioid therapy for chronic non-cancer pain: a review and comparison of treatment guidelines | url = | journal = Pain Physician | volume = 17 | issue = 5| pages = 401\u201314 | pmid = 25247898 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Schug | first1 = SA | last2 = Chandrasena | first2 = C | date = Jan 2015 | title = Pain management of the cancer patient | url = | journal = Expert Opin Pharmacother | volume = 16 | issue = 1| pages = 5\u201315 | doi = 10.1517/14656566.2015.980723 | pmid = 25479712 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = McLean | first1 = S | last2 = Twomey | first2 = F | date = Aug 2015 | title = Methods of Rotation From Another Strong Opioid to Methadone for the Management of Cancer Pain: A Systematic Review of the Available Evidence | url = | journal = J Pain Symptom Manage | volume = 50 | issue = 2| pages = 248\u201359 | doi = 10.1016/j.jpainsymman.2015.02.029 | pmid = 25896106 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Gudin | first1 = J | last2 = Fudin | first2 = J | last3 = Nalamachu | first3 = S | date = Jan 2016 | title = Levorphanol use: past, present and future | url = | journal = Postgrad Med | volume = 128 | issue = 1| pages = 46\u201353 | doi = 10.1080/00325481.2016.1128308 | pmid = 26635068 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Mercadante | first1 = S | last2 = Bruera | first2 = E | date = Mar 2016 | title = Opioid switching in cancer pain: From the beginning to nowadays | url = | journal = Crit Rev Oncol Hematol | volume = 99 | issue = | pages = 241\u20138 | doi = 10.1016/j.critrevonc.2015.12.011 | pmid = 26806145 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Dima | first1 = D | last2 = Tomuleasa | first2 = C | last3 = Frinc | first3 = I | last4 = Pasca | first4 = S | last5 = Magdo | first5 = L | last6 = Berindan-Neagoe | first6 = I | last7 = Muresan | first7 = M | last8 = Lisencu | first8 = C | last9 = Irimie | first9 = A | last10 = Zdrenghea | first10 = M | date = Feb 2017 | title = The use of rotation to fentanyl in cancer-related pain | journal = J Pain Res | volume = 10 | issue = | pages = 341\u2013348 | doi = 10.2147/JPR.S121920 | pmid = 28223843 | pmc = 5310636 }}</ref> Additionally, newer studies may explore which patient populations can benefit the most from opioid rotation and which populations can have their pain managed by other means.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Opioid-induced hyperalgesia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www3.us.elsevierhealth.com/pain/charts.html Equianalgesic Charts]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130227022743/http://www.americanpainsociety.org/library/cp_guidelines.htm American Pain Society Guidelines]\n*[http://www.healthquality.va.gov/Chronic_Opioid_Therapy_COT.asp Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Opioid Therapy for Chronic Pain]\n*[http://clincalc.com/Opioids Online opioid equianalgesia calculator] Electronic calculator that includes logic for bidirectional and dose-dependent conversions\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 19735901 | doi=10.1016/j.jpainsymman.2009.06.004 | volume=38 | title=Opioid equianalgesic tables: are they all equally dangerous? | year=2009 | journal=J Pain Symptom Manage | pages=409\u201317  | last1 = Shaheen | first1 = PE | last2 = Walsh | first2 = D | last3 = Lasheen | first3 = W | last4 = Davis | first4 = MP | last5 = Lagman | first5 = RL}}\n\n{{Opioidergics}}\n\n[[Category:Analgesics]]\n[[Category:Anesthesia]]\n[[Category:Medical terminology]]\n[[Category:Nociception]]\n[[Category:Opioids]]\n[[Category:Pain]]\n[[Category:Clinical pharmacology]]\n", "text_old": "'''Opioid rotation'''&nbsp;or&nbsp;'''opioid switching'''&nbsp;is the process of changing one opioid to another to improve [[pain]] control or reduce unwanted [[side effect]]s.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite journal |last1=Kraychete |first1=DC |last2=Sakata |first2=RK |title=Use and rotation of opioids in chronic non-oncologic pain. |journal=Revista Brasileira de Anestesiologia |date=July 2012 |volume=62 |issue=4 |pages=554\u201362 |doi=10.1016/S0034-7094(12)70155-1 |pmid=