{"title_page": "Indian locomotive class WAM-4", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2019}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox locomotive\n | name             = Indian Railways WAM-4\n | image            = File:WAM4 Ennore.JPG\n | caption          = AJJ WAM-4 hauling an express train\n | powertype        = Electric\n | builddate        = 1970\u20131983\n | rebuilddate      = 1978\u20131983 to WAG-5\n | gauge            = {{Track gauge|66in|lk=on}}\n | builder          = [[Chittaranjan Locomotive Works]], [[India]]\n | totalproduction  = '''WAM-4:''' 500\n | uicclass         = Co\u2032Co\u2032\n | axleload         = {{convert|18.8|t}}\n | electricsystem   = {{25 kV 50 Hz}} [[Overhead line|Overhead]] \n | collectionmethod = [[Pantograph (rail)|Pantograph]]\n | poweroutput      = {{convert|3640|hp|kW|-1|abbr=on}}\n | maxspeed         = {{convert|110|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} \n | tractiveeffort   = {{convert|33840|kgf|kN lbf|abbr=on}}\n | operator         = [[Indian Railways]]\n | fleetnumbers     = 20400\u201320699, 21200\u201321399\n | nicknames        = Ananth, RAJATABHA, Surubhi, Navchetna, Sukh Sagar Naveen\n | locale           = All over [[India]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Indian locomotive class WAM-4''' is a very successful class of workhorse 25 [[Volt|kV]] [[Alternating current|AC]] [[electric locomotive]]s used in [[India]].  The first member of the class was indigenously designed and built by [[Chittaranjan Locomotive Works|CLW]] in 1970. The class was produced until 1983.\n\nThe locomotives in the class feature [[rheostatic braking]], and MU capability. They use the same [[power bogie]]s as the successful [[Indian locomotive class WDM-2|WDM-2]] class of [[diesel-electric]] locomotives. Being designed specially for mixed traffic, the WAM-4 class has rendered excellent service.\nNow, most of these are used exclusively for passenger traffic.\nThis class proved so successful by virtue of its ruggedness suitable for Indian conditions and simplicity of maintenance, that IR used this basic design for a number of other locos later (WCAM-1, WAG-5A, WCG-2, and some WAP models). A single WAM-4 can generally haul up to a 24-coach passenger rake. However, with the advent of new 3-phase locos like WAP - 5 and WAP - 7, the WAM - 4 locomotives were relegated to hauling smaller passenger trains. Also, due to the aging fleet the WAM - 4 locomotives are being rapidly scrapped and withdrawn from mainline duties.\n\nThis loco class has been seen in many variations, as a lot of workshops and sheds have carried out their own enhancements or modifications to the basic loco design. This loco has the widest variety of liveries, with each loco shed having its own livery.\nAlthough the code indicates a mixed-use loco, most WAM-4's ended up hauling passenger trains. They have been used for regularly hauling freight only in a few locations (Arakkonam - Renigunta, Kirandul-Kottavalasa and other SER sections). Max. speed 110&nbsp;km/h.Variants include WAM-4P D (dual brakes), WAM-4P R (??), WAM-4P DB 6P, WAM-4 6P DB HS, and WAM-4 6P D (these are for superfast trains), WAM-4P DB 3P and WAM-4 2S-3P (some superfasts, passengers), and WAM-4P DB 4P (generally for stopping passengers). The 'DB' or 'D' generally, but perhaps not always, indicates dual-brake capability. 'HS' may be for 'high speed'.'2S', '3P', '6P', etc. indicate traction motors connected in series or parallel. The WAM-4 has six traction motors, and originally they were wired to be available in different configurations at different power settings. At notches up to 14, all motors were in series (at notch 14 all resistors dropping out); up to notch 21 in series-parallel combinations (three pairs of motors in series, the pairs themselves being in parallel); and further notches with all motors in parallel (at notch 30 all motors are in parallel with resistors dropping out). This is the original configuration of the WCAM-x series of locos too. The WAM-4 locos were later reconfigured to have all motors always in parallel (6P variants) or with the three series-connected pairs in parallel (2S 3P variants). Some WAM-4 locos from CLW are thought to have had the 2S 3P configuration right from the start. The 2S 3P configuration was better for the mixed traffic loads especially as it allowed the locos to start hauling larger loads without stalling. With increasing use of the WAM-4 locos for passenger traffic the all-parallel configuration was deemed more desirable since it allowed higher speeds and higher acceleration.\n\nMost of the WAM-4 locos now have their MU capability disabled as [[Research Design and Standards Organization|RDSO]] disapproves of these locos running MU'd over 100&nbsp;km/h.\n<ref>http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-loco2e.html</ref>\n\n==Loco Sheds still holding WAM-4.==\n*'''Loco Shed Asansol-''' 3\n*'''Loco Shed Ghaziabad-''' 1\n*'''Loco Shed Ludhiana-''' 1\n*'''Loco Shed Jhansi-''' 1\n*'''Loco Shed Kanpur-''' 3\n*'''Loco Shed Tatanagar-''' 4\n*'''Loco Shed Bhilai-''' 4<br/ >In total 17 locomotives as of 01-03-2020 are there but 9 of them are overaged condemned and 8 of them are inferior in service.\n('''Note-'''Before updating the information here anybody should check out the railways current official data first in the  '''Source''' link then change the data.)\n<br/ >'''Source:''' http://elocos.railnet.gov.in/\n\n==Technical specifications<ref>[http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-loco2e.html#loco Indian AC electric loco information]</ref>==\n{| class=wikitable\n|Traction Motors\n|Alstom TAO 659 A1 (575&nbsp;kW, 750 V). Six motors, axle-hung, nose-suspended, force-ventilated. \n|-\n|Gear Ratio\n|15:62 originally (and still for WAM-4 2S3P), now many variations, 21:58 being common for WAM-4 6P locos.\n|-\n|Transformer\n|Heil BOT 3460 A, 22.5 kV / 3460 kVA. \n|-\n|Rectifiers\n|Two silicon rectifier cells, 1270 V / 1000 A each cubicle. \n|-\n|Pantographs\n|Two Faiveley AM-12. \n|-\n|Hauling capacity\n|{{convert|2010|t|abbr=on}} \n|-\n|Current Ratings\n|(WAM-4 6P) 1100A/10min, 750A continuous\n|}\n\n==Image Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"180\" heights=\"150\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:VSKP-Nanded Express exits Moula Ali.jpg|WAM 4 series loco 20491 from Vadodara Shed VSKP-Nanded Express\nFile:WAM4 loco at Moulaali.jpg|WAM 4 series loco 21226 from Visakhapatnam Shed spotted at [[Moula-Ali|Moula Ali]]\nFile:WAM 4 series loco at Visakhapatnam.jpg|WAM 4 series loco 21219 from [[Arakkonam]] Shed spotted at [[Visakhapatnam Junction]]\nFile:13022 (Raxaul-Howrah) Mithila Express 01.jpg|13022 (Raxaul - [[Howrah Junction railway station|Howrah]]) Mithila Express with [[Howrah Junction railway station|HWH]] WAM 4 21281 based at katni shed\nFile:A WAM-4 class Locomotive at Secunderabad.jpg|WAM-4P loco of [[Vijayawada Junction railway station|Vijayawada]] Shed spotted at [[Secunderabad Junction railway station|Secunderabad]]\nFile:WAM 4 with the Malwa Express.jpg|WAM 4 with the [[Malwa Express]]\nFile:12295 (SBC-PNBE) Sanghamitra Express 01.jpg|12295 (SBC-PNBE) Sanghamitra Express from [[Mughalsarai]] Shed\nFile:Howrah bound 12814 (Tatanagar-Howrah) Steel Express.jpg|Howrah bound 12814 (Tatanagar-Howrah) Steel Express with WAM4 series loco of Tata shed\n</gallery>\n\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[History of rail transport in India]]\n*[[Indian Railways]]\n*[[Locomotives of India]]\n*[[Rail transport in India]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Hughes-IndianLocos4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Indian locomotive class WAM4}}\n*[http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-specs.html#WAG-9 Specifications]\n*[http://www.irfca.org India railway fan club]\n\n{{Broad gauge locomotives of India |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Electric locomotives of India]]\n[[Category:25 kV AC locomotives]]\n[[Category:Co-Co locomotives]]\n[[Category:Railway locomotives introduced in 1970]]\n[[Category:5 ft 6 in gauge locomotives]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2019}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox locomotive\n | name             = Indian Railways WAM-4\n | image            = File:WAM4 Ennore.JPG\n | caption          = AJJ WAM-4 hauling an express train\n | powertype        = Electric\n | builddate        = 1970\u20131983\n | rebuilddate      = 1978\u20131983 to WAG-5\n | gauge            = {{Track gauge|66in|lk=on}}\n | builder          = [[Chittaranjan Locomotive Works]], [[India]]\n | totalproduction  = '''WAM-4:''' 500\n | uicclass         = Co\u2032Co\u2032\n | axleload         = {{convert|18.8|t}}\n | electricsystem   = {{25 kV 50 Hz}} [[Overhead line|Overhead]] \n | collectionmethod = [[Pantograph (rail)|Pantograph]]\n | poweroutput      = {{convert|3640|hp|kW|-1|abbr=on}}\n | maxspeed         = {{convert|110|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} \n | tractiveeffort   = {{convert|33840|kgf|kN lbf|abbr=on}}\n | operator         = [[Indian Railways]]\n | fleetnumbers     = 20400\u201320699, 21200\u201321399\n | nicknames        = Ananth, RAJATABHA, Surubhi, Navchetna, Sukh Sagar Naveen\n | locale           = All over [[India]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Indian locomotive class WAM-4''' is a very successful class of workhorse 25 [[Volt|kV]] [[Alternating current|AC]] [[electric locomotive]]s used in [[India]].  The first member of the class was indigenously designed and built by [[Chittaranjan Locomotive Works|CLW]] in 1970. The class was produced until 1983.\n\nThe locomotives in the class feature [[rheostatic braking]], and MU capability. They use the same [[power bogie]]s as the successful [[Indian locomotive class WDM-2|WDM-2]] class of [[diesel-electric]] locomotives. Being designed specially for mixed traffic, the WAM-4 class has rendered excellent service.\nNow, most of these are used exclusively for passenger traffic.\nThis class proved so successful by virtue of its ruggedness suitable for Indian conditions and simplicity of maintenance, that IR used this basic design for a number of other locos later (WCAM-1, WAG-5A, WCG-2, and some WAP models). A single WAM-4 can generally haul up to a 24-coach passenger rake. However, with the advent of new 3-phase locos like WAP - 5 and WAP - 7, the WAM - 4 locomotives were relegated to hauling smaller passenger trains. Also, due to the aging fleet the WAM - 4 locomotives are being rapidly scrapped and withdrawn from mainline duties.\n\nThis loco class has been seen in many variations, as a lot of workshops and sheds have carried out their own enhancements or modifications to the basic loco design. This loco has the widest variety of liveries, with each loco shed having its own livery.\nAlthough the code indicates a mixed-use loco, most WAM-4's ended up hauling passenger trains. They have been used for regularly hauling freight only in a few locations (Arakkonam - Renigunta, Kirandul-Kottavalasa and other SER sections). Max. speed 110&nbsp;km/h.Variants include WAM-4P D (dual brakes), WAM-4P R (??), WAM-4P DB 6P, WAM-4 6P DB HS, and WAM-4 6P D (these are for superfast trains), WAM-4P DB 3P and WAM-4 2S-3P (some superfasts, passengers), and WAM-4P DB 4P (generally for stopping passengers). The 'DB' or 'D' generally, but perhaps not always, indicates dual-brake capability. 'HS' may be for 'high speed'.'2S', '3P', '6P', etc. indicate traction motors connected in series or parallel. The WAM-4 has six traction motors, and originally they were wired to be available in different configurations at different power settings. At notches up to 14, all motors were in series (at notch 14 all resistors dropping out); up to notch 21 in series-parallel combinations (three pairs of motors in series, the pairs themselves being in parallel); and further notches with all motors in parallel (at notch 30 all motors are in parallel with resistors dropping out). This is the original configuration of the WCAM-x series of locos too. The WAM-4 locos were later reconfigured to have all motors always in parallel (6P variants) or with the three series-connected pairs in parallel (2S 3P variants). Some WAM-4 locos from CLW are thought to have had the 2S 3P configuration right from the start. The 2S 3P configuration was better for the mixed traffic loads especially as it allowed the locos to start hauling larger loads without stalling. With increasing use of the WAM-4 locos for passenger traffic the all-parallel configuration was deemed more desirable since it allowed higher speeds and higher acceleration.\n\nMost of the WAM-4 locos now have their MU capability disabled as [[Research Design and Standards Organization|RDSO]] disapproves of these locos running MU'd over 100&nbsp;km/h.\n<ref>http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-loco2e.html</ref>\n\n==Loco Sheds still holding WAM-4.==\n*'''Loco Shed Asansol-''' 3\n*'''Loco Shed Ghaziabad-''' 1\n*'''Loco Shed Ludhiana-''' 1\n*'''Loco Shed Jhansi-''' 1\n*'''Loco Shed Kanpur-''' 3\n*'''Loco Shed Tatanagar-''' 4\n*'''Loco Shed Bhilai-''' 4<br/ >In total 17 locomotives as of 01-03-2020 are there but 9 of them are overaged condemned and 8 of them are inferior in service.\n('''Note-'''Before updating the information here anybody should check out the railways current official data first in the  '''Source''' link then change the data.)\n<br/ >'''Source:''' http://elocos.railnet.gov.in/\n\n==Image Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"180\" heights=\"150\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:VSKP-Nanded Express exits Moula Ali.jpg|WAM 4 series loco 20491 from Vadodara Shed VSKP-Nanded Express\nFile:WAM4 loco at Moulaali.jpg|WAM 4 series loco 21226 from Visakhapatnam Shed spotted at [[Moula-Ali|Moula Ali]]\nFile:WAM 4 series loco at Visakhapatnam.jpg|WAM 4 series loco 21219 from [[Arakkonam]] Shed spotted at [[Visakhapatnam Junction]]\nFile:13022 (Raxaul-Howrah) Mithila Express 01.jpg|13022 (Raxaul - [[Howrah Junction railway station|Howrah]]) Mithila Express with [[Howrah Junction railway station|HWH]] WAM 4 21281 based at katni shed\nFile:A WAM-4 class Locomotive at Secunderabad.jpg|WAM-4P 